# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: lidar-sensors-deep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/beam-steering] In radio and radar systems, beam steering may be accomplished by switching the antenna elements or by changing the relative phases of the RF signals driving the elements.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/beam-steering] As a result, this directs the transmit signal towards an intended receiver.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/beam-steering] In recent days, beam steering is playing a significant role in 5G communication because of quasi-optic nature of 5G frequencies.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/beam-steering] The simplest method *beam tilt* is mechanical beam tilt, where the antenna is physically mounted in such a manner as to lower the angle of the signal on one side.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/beam-steering] However, this also raises it on the other side, making it useful in only very limited situations.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/beam-steering] More common is electrical beam tilt, where the phasing between antenna elements is tweaked to make the signal go down (usually) in all directions.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/beam-steering] This is extremely useful when the antenna is at a very high point, and the edge of the signal is likely to miss the target (broadcast audience, cellphone users, etc.) entirely.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/beam-steering] With electrical tilting, front and back lobes tilt in the same direction.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/beam-steering] For example, an electrical downtilt will make both the front lobe and the back lobe tilt down.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/beam-steering] This is the property used in the above example where the signal is pointed down in all directions.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/beam-steering] On the contrary, mechanical downtilting will make the front lobe tilt down and the back lobe tilt up.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/beam-steering] In almost all practical cases, antennas are only tilted down – though tilting up is technically possible.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/beam-steering] The use of purely electrical tilt with no mechanical tilt is an attractive choice for aesthetic reasons which are very important for operators seeking acceptance of integrated antennas in visible locations.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/beam-steering] In GSM and UMTS cellular networks, mechanical tilt is almost always fixed whereas electrical tilt can be controlled using remote actuators and position sensors, thus reducing operating expenses.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/beam-steering] Remote electrical tilt is abbreviated as RET and it is part of the Antenna Interface Standards Group's open specification for the control interface of antenna devices.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/beam-steering] Occasionally, mechanical and electrical tilt will be used together in order to create greater beam tilt in one direction than the other, mainly to accommodate unusual terrain.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/beam-steering] Along with null fill, beam tilt is the essential parameter controlling the focus of radio communications, and together they can create almost infinite combinations of 3-D radiation patterns for any situation.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/beam-steering] Different studies in beam tilt optimization focus on Coverage-Capacity Optimization (CCO), for which the goal is to control the beam tilt in order to jointly optimize the radio coverage and capacity in the network cells and reduce interference from neighbouring cells.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/beam-steering] **Data-driven algorithms** : consist of optimization strategies based on the use learning techniques based on the availability of network data (e.g.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/beam-steering] Contextual Bandit (CB) techniques), or by directly interacting with the environment (e.g.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/beam-steering] In acoustics, beam steering is used to direct the audio from loudspeakers to a specific location in the listening area.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/beam-steering] This is done by changing the magnitude and phase of two or more loudspeakers installed in a column where the combined sound is added and cancelled at the required position.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/beam-steering] Commercially, this type of loudspeaker arrangement is known as a line array.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/beam-steering] This technique has been around for many years but since the emergence of modern digital signal processing (DSP) technology there are now many commercially available products on the market.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/beam-steering] Beam steering and directivity Control using DSP was pioneered in the early 1990s by Duran Audio who launched a technology called DDC (Digital Directivity Control).
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/beam-steering] In optical systems, beam steering may be accomplished by changing the refractive index of the medium through which the beam is transmitted or by the use of mirrors, prisms, lenses, or rotating diffraction gratings.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/beam-steering] Examples of optical beam steering approaches include mechanical mirror-based gimbals or beam-director units, galvanometer mechanisms that rotate mirrors, Risley prisms, phased-array optics, and microelectromechanical systems using micro-mirrors.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/beam-steering] The scope of beam-steering technologies has broadened significantly with innovations that serve both traditional applications and emerging demands in fields such as satellite communication, radar, and 5G networks.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/beam-steering] Traditional methods like parabolic reflectors and phased arrays are now complemented by Reflectarray (RA) and Transmitarray (TA) antennas.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/beam-steering] These designs serve as high-gain, planar alternatives with advantages in cost, efficiency, and scalability, meeting modern requirements for compact and lightweight systems.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/beam-steering] One of the latest approaches in beam steering involves Near-Field Meta-Steering (NFMS), which uses phase-gradient metasurfaces placed in close proximity to a feed antenna.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/beam-steering] This method achieves 3D beam steering by employing compact structures that allow wide-angle control over both elevation and azimuth, proving highly effective for systems where space and profile height are restricted.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/beam-steering] Beam steering has also found essential applications in high-speed, interference-free communication for defense and civilian markets.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/beam-steering] Satellite-based communication systems, for example, require dual-band beam-steering capabilities to handle uplink and downlink data streams simultaneously.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/beam-steering] The development of beam-steering antennas for Satellite Communication on the Move (SOTM) systems highlights the need for antennas that are not only efficient but also lightweight, low-profile, and cost-effective.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/beam-steering] Challenges remain, including addressing cost constraints and achieving higher scanning speeds and wider bandwidths.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] In this view, the viewer flies down to the rainforest canopy and flies through the virtual leaves.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] This visualisation shows an airplane collecting a 50 km swathe of lidar data over the Brazilian rainforest.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] For ground-level features, colours range from deep brown to tan.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Vegetation heights are depicted in shades of green, where dark greens are closest to the ground and light greens are the highest.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Lidar has terrestrial, airborne, and mobile uses.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] It is commonly used to make high-resolution maps, with applications in surveying, geodesy, geomatics, archaeology, geography, geology, geomorphology, seismology, forestry, atmospheric physics, laser guidance, airborne laser swathe mapping (ALSM), and laser altimetry.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] It is used to make digital 3-D representations of areas on the Earth's surface and ocean bottom of the intertidal and near coastal zone by varying the wavelength of light.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] It has also been increasingly used in control and navigation for autonomous cars and for the helicopter *Ingenuity* on its record-setting flights over the terrain of Mars.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Lidar has since been used extensively for atmospheric research and meteorology.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Lidar instruments fitted to aircraft and satellites carry out surveying and mapping – a recent example being the U.S.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Geological Survey Experimental Advanced Airborne Research Lidar.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] NASA has identified lidar as a key technology for enabling autonomous precision safe landing of future robotic and crewed lunar-landing vehicles.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] The essential concept of lidar was originated by E.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Synge in 1930, who envisaged the use of powerful searchlights to probe the atmosphere.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Under the direction of Malcolm Stitch, the Hughes Aircraft Company introduced the first lidar-like system in 1961, shortly after the invention of the laser.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Intended for satellite tracking, this system combined laser-focused imaging with the ability to calculate distances by measuring the time for a signal to return using appropriate sensors and data acquisition electronics.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] It was originally called "Colidar" an acronym for "coherent light detecting and ranging", derived from the term "radar", itself an acronym for "radio detection and ranging".
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] All laser rangefinders, laser altimeters and lidar units are derived from the early colidar systems.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] The first practical terrestrial application of a colidar system was the "Colidar Mark II", a large rifle-like laser rangefinder produced in 1963, which had a range of 11 km and an accuracy of 4.5 m, to be used for military targeting.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] The first mention of lidar as a stand-alone word in 1963 suggests that it originated as a portmanteau of "light" and "radar": "Eventually the laser may provide an extremely sensitive detector of particular wavelengths from distant objects.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Meanwhile, it is being used to study the Moon by 'lidar' (light radar) ..." The name "photonic radar" is sometimes used to mean visible-spectrum range finding like lidar.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Lidar's first applications were in meteorology, for which the National Center for Atmospheric Research used it to measure clouds and pollution.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] The general public became aware of the accuracy and usefulness of lidar systems in 1971 during the Apollo 15 mission, when astronauts used a laser altimeter to map the surface of the Moon.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Although the English language no longer treats "radar" as an acronym, (i.e., uncapitalized), the word "lidar" was capitalized as "LIDAR" or "LiDAR" in some publications beginning in the 1980s.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Various publications refer to lidar as "LIDAR", "LiDAR", "LIDaR", or "Lidar".
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] The USGS uses both "LIDAR" and "lidar", sometimes in the same document; the *New York Times* predominantly uses "lidar" for staff-written articles, although contributing news feeds such as Reuters may use Lidar.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Lidar uses ultraviolet, visible, or near infrared light to image objects.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] It can target a wide range of materials, including non-metallic objects, rocks, rain, chemical compounds, aerosols, clouds and even single molecules.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] A narrow laser beam can map physical features with very high resolutions; for example, an aircraft can map terrain at 30-centimetre (12 in) resolution or better.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Wavelengths vary to suit the target: from about 10 micrometers (infrared) to approximately 250 nanometers (ultraviolet).
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Typically, light is reflected via backscattering, as opposed to pure reflection one might find with a mirror.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Different types of scattering are used for different lidar applications: most commonly Rayleigh scattering, Mie scattering, Raman scattering, and fluorescence.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Suitable combinations of wavelengths can allow remote mapping of atmospheric contents by identifying wavelength-dependent changes in the intensity of the returned signal.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] The name "photonic radar" is sometimes used to mean visible-spectrum range finding like lidar, although photonic radar more strictly refers to radio-frequency range finding using photonics components.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] where *c* is the speed of light, *d* is the distance between the detector and the object or surface being detected, and *t* is the time spent for the laser light to travel to the object or surface being detected, then travel back to the detector.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] The two kinds of lidar detection schemes are "incoherent" or direct energy detection (which principally measures amplitude changes of the reflected light) and coherent detection (best for measuring Doppler shifts, or changes in the phase of the reflected light).
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Coherent systems generally use optical heterodyne detection.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] This is more sensitive than direct detection and allows them to operate at much lower power, but requires more complex transceivers.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Both types employ pulse models: either *micropulse* or *high energy*.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Micropulse systems utilize intermittent bursts of energy.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] They developed as a result of ever-increasing computer power, combined with advances in laser technology.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] They use considerably less energy in the laser, typically on the order of one microjoule, and are often "eye-safe", meaning they can be used without safety precautions.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] 600–1,000 nm lasers are most common for non-scientific applications.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] The maximum power of the laser is limited, or an automatic shut-off system which turns the laser off at specific altitudes is used in order to make it eye-safe for the people on the ground.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] One common alternative, 1,550 nm lasers, are eye-safe at relatively high power levels since this wavelength is strongly absorbed by water and barely reaches the retina, though camera sensors can still get damaged.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] A trade-off though is that current detector technology is less advanced, so these wavelengths are generally used at longer ranges with lower accuracies.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] They are also used for military applications because 1,550 nm is not visible in night vision goggles, unlike the shorter 1,000 nm infrared laser.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Airborne topographic mapping lidars generally use 1,064 nm diode-pumped YAG lasers, while bathymetric (underwater depth research) systems generally use 532 nm frequency-doubled diode pumped YAG lasers because 532 nm penetrates water with much less attenuation than 1,064 nm.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Laser settings include the laser repetition rate (which controls the data collection speed).
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Pulse length is generally an attribute of the laser cavity length, the number of passes required through the gain material (YAG, YLF, etc.), and Q-switch (pulsing) speed.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Better target resolution is achieved with shorter pulses, provided the lidar receiver detectors and electronics have sufficient bandwidth.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] A phased array can illuminate any direction by using a microscopic array of individual antennas.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Controlling the timing (phase) of each antenna steers a cohesive signal in a specific direction.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Phased arrays have been used in radar since the 1940s.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] On the order of a million optical antennas are used to see a radiation pattern of a certain size in a certain direction.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] To achieve this the phase of each individual antenna (emitter) are precisely controlled.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] It is very difficult, if possible at all, to use the same technique in a lidar.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] The main problems are that all individual emitters must be coherent (technically coming from the same "master" oscillator or laser source), have dimensions about the wavelength of the emitted light (1 micron range) to act as a point source with their phases being controlled with high accuracy.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Microelectromechanical mirrors (MEMS) are not entirely solid-state.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] However, their tiny form factor provides many of the same cost benefits.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] A single laser is directed to a single mirror that can be reoriented to view any part of the target field.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] However, MEMS systems generally operate in a single plane (left to right).
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] To add a second dimension generally requires a second mirror that moves up and down.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Alternatively, another laser can hit the same mirror from another angle.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] MEMS systems can be disrupted by shock/vibration and may require repeated calibration.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Image development speed is affected by the speed at which they are scanned.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Options to scan the azimuth and elevation include dual oscillating plane mirrors, a combination with a polygon mirror, and a dual axis scanner.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Optic choices affect the angular resolution and range that can be detected.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] A hole mirror or a beam splitter are options to collect a return signal.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Two main photodetector technologies are used in lidar: solid-state photodetectors, such as silicon avalanche photodiodes, or photomultipliers.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] The sensitivity of the receiver is another parameter that has to be balanced in a lidar design.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Lidar sensors mounted on mobile platforms such as airplanes or satellites require instrumentation to determine the absolute position and orientation of the sensor.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Such devices generally include a Global Positioning System receiver and an inertial measurement unit (IMU).
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Lidar uses active sensors that supply their own illumination source.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] The energy source hits objects and the reflected energy is detected and measured by sensors.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Distance to the object is determined by recording the time between transmitted and backscattered pulses and by using the speed of light to calculate the distance traveled.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Flash lidar allows for 3-D imaging because of the camera's ability to emit a larger flash and sense the spatial relationships and dimensions of area of interest with the returned energy.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] This allows for more accurate imaging because the captured frames do not need to be stitched together, and the system is not sensitive to platform motion.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] 3-D imaging can be achieved using both scanning and non-scanning systems.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] "3-D gated viewing laser radar" is a non-scanning laser ranging system that applies a pulsed laser and a fast gated camera.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Research has begun for virtual beam steering using digital light processing (DLP) technology.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Imaging lidar can also be performed using arrays of high speed detectors and modulation sensitive detector arrays typically built on single chips using complementary metal–oxide–semiconductor (CMOS) and hybrid CMOS/charge-coupled device (CCD) fabrication techniques.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] In these devices each pixel performs some local processing such as demodulation or gating at high speed, downconverting the signals to video rate so that the array can be read like a camera.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Using this technique many thousands of pixels / channels may be acquired simultaneously.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] High resolution 3-D lidar cameras use homodyne detection with an electronic CCD or CMOS shutter.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] A coherent imaging lidar uses synthetic array heterodyne detection to enable a staring single element receiver to act as though it were an imaging array.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] In 2014, Lincoln Laboratory announced a new imaging chip with more than 16,384 pixels, each able to image a single photon, enabling them to capture a wide area in a single image.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] An earlier generation of the technology with one fourth as many pixels was dispatched by the U.S. military after the January 2010 Haiti earthquake.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] A single pass by a business jet at 3,000 m (10,000 ft) over Port-au-Prince was able to capture instantaneous snapshots of 600 m (2,000 ft) squares of the city at a resolution of 30 cm (1 ft), displaying the precise height of rubble strewn in city streets.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] The new system is ten times better, and could produce much larger maps more quickly.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] The chip uses indium gallium arsenide (InGaAs), which operates in the infrared spectrum at a relatively long wavelength that allows for higher power and longer ranges.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] In many applications, such as self-driving cars, the new system will lower costs by not requiring a mechanical component to aim the chip.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] InGaAs uses less hazardous wavelengths than conventional silicon detectors, which operate at visual wavelengths.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] New technologies for infrared single-photon counting lidar are advancing rapidly, including arrays and cameras in a variety of semiconductor and superconducting platforms.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Lidar can be oriented to nadir, zenith, or laterally.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] For example, lidar altimeters look down, an atmospheric lidar looks up, and lidar-based collision avoidance systems are side-looking.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Lidar applications can be divided into airborne and terrestrial types.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] The two types require scanners with varying specifications based on the data's purpose, the size of the area to be captured, the range of measurement desired, the cost of equipment, and more.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Spaceborne platforms are also possible, see satellite laser altimetry.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Airborne lidar (also *airborne laser scanning*) is when a laser scanner, while attached to an aircraft during flight, creates a 3-D point cloud model of the landscape.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] This is currently the most detailed and accurate method of creating digital elevation models, replacing photogrammetry.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] One major advantage in comparison with photogrammetry is the ability to filter out reflections from vegetation from the point cloud model to create a digital terrain model which represents ground surfaces such as rivers, paths, cultural heritage sites, etc., which are concealed by trees.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Within the category of airborne lidar, there is sometimes a distinction made between high-altitude and low-altitude applications, but the main difference is a reduction in both accuracy and point density of data acquired at higher altitudes.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Airborne lidar can also be used to create bathymetric models in shallow water.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] The main constituents of airborne lidar include digital elevation models (DEM) and digital surface models (DSM).
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] The points and ground points are the vectors of discrete points while DEM and DSM are interpolated raster grids of discrete points.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] The process also involves capturing of digital aerial photographs.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] To interpret deep-seated landslides for example, under the cover of vegetation, scarps, tension cracks or tipped trees airborne lidar is used.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Airborne lidar digital elevation models can see through the canopy of forest cover, perform detailed measurements of scarps, erosion and tilting of electric poles.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Airborne lidar data is processed using a toolbox called Toolbox for Lidar Data Filtering and Forest Studies (TIFFS) for lidar data filtering and terrain study software.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] The data is interpolated to digital terrain models using the software.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] The laser is directed at the region to be mapped and each point's height above the ground is calculated by subtracting the original z-coordinate from the corresponding digital terrain model elevation.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Based on this height above the ground the non-vegetation data is obtained which may include objects such as buildings, electric power lines, flying birds, insects, etc.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] The rest of the points are treated as vegetation and used for modeling and mapping.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Within each of these plots, lidar metrics are calculated by calculating statistics such as mean, standard deviation, skewness, percentiles, quadratic mean, etc.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Multiple commercial lidar systems for unmanned aerial vehicles are currently on the market.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] These platforms can systematically scan large areas, or provide a cheaper alternative to manned aircraft for smaller scanning operations.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] The airborne lidar bathymetric technological system involves the measurement of time of flight of a signal from a source to its return to the sensor.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] The data acquisition technique involves a sea floor mapping component and a ground truth component that includes video transects and sampling.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] It works using a green spectrum (532 nm) laser beam.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Two beams are projected onto a fast rotating mirror, which creates an array of points.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] One of the beams penetrates the water and also detects the bottom surface of the water under favorable conditions.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Water depth measurable by lidar depends on the clarity of the water and the absorption of the wavelength used.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Water is most transparent to green and blue light, so these will penetrate deepest in clean water.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Blue-green light of 532 nm produced by frequency doubled solid-state IR laser output is the standard for airborne bathymetry.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] This light can penetrate water but pulse strength attenuates exponentially with distance traveled through the water.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Lidar can measure depths from about 0.9 to 40 m (3 to 131 ft), with vertical accuracy in the order of 15 cm (6 in).
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] The surface reflection makes water shallower than about 0.9 m (3 ft) difficult to resolve, and absorption limits the maximum depth.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Turbidity causes scattering and has a significant role in determining the maximum depth that can be resolved in most situations, and dissolved pigments can increase absorption depending on wavelength.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Other reports indicate that water penetration tends to be between two and three times Secchi depth.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Bathymetric lidar is most useful in the 0–10 m (0–33 ft) depth range in coastal mapping.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] On average in fairly clear coastal seawater lidar can penetrate to about 7 m (23 ft), and in turbid water up to about 3 m (10 ft).
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] An average value found by Saputra et al, 2021, is for the green laser light to penetrate water about one and a half to two times Secchi depth in Indonesian waters.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Water temperature and salinity have an effect on the refractive index which has a small effect on the depth calculation.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] The data obtained shows the full extent of the land surface exposed above the sea floor.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] This technique is extremely useful as it will play an important role in the major sea floor mapping program.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] The mapping yields onshore topography as well as underwater elevations.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Sea floor reflectance imaging is another solution product from this system which can benefit mapping of underwater habitats.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] This technique has been used for three-dimensional image mapping of California's waters using a hydrographic lidar.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Airborne lidar systems were traditionally able to acquire only a few peak returns, while more recent systems acquire and digitize the entire reflected signal.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Scientists analysed the waveform signal for extracting peak returns using Gaussian decomposition.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Zhuang et al, 2017 used this approach for estimating aboveground biomass.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Handling the huge amounts of full-waveform data is difficult.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Therefore, Gaussian decomposition of the waveforms is effective, since it reduces the data and is supported by existing workflows that support interpretation of 3-D point clouds.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Recent studies investigated voxelisation.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] The intensities of the waveform samples are inserted into a voxelised space (3-D grayscale image) building up a 3-D representation of the scanned area.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Related metrics and information can then be extracted from that voxelised space.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Structural information can be extracted using 3-D metrics from local areas and there is a case study that used the voxelisation approach for detecting dead standing eucalypt trees in Australia.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Terrestrial applications of lidar (also *terrestrial laser scanning*) happen on the Earth's surface and can be either stationary or mobile.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Stationary terrestrial scanning is most common as a survey method, for example in conventional topography, monitoring, cultural heritage documentation and forensics.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] The 3-D point clouds acquired from these types of scanners can be matched with digital images taken of the scanned area from the scanner's location to create realistic looking 3-D models in a relatively short time when compared to other technologies.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Each point in the point cloud is given the colour of the pixel from the image taken at the same location and direction as the laser beam that created the point.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Terrestrial lidar mapping involves a process of occupancy grid map generation.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] The process involves an array of cells divided into grids which employ a process to store the height values when lidar data falls into the respective grid cell.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] A binary map is then created by applying a particular threshold to the cell values for further processing.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] The next step is to process the radial distance and z-coordinates from each scan to identify which 3-D points correspond to each of the specified grid cell leading to the process of data formation.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Mobile lidar (also *mobile laser scanning*) is when two or more scanners are attached to a moving vehicle to collect data along a path.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] These scanners are almost always paired with other kinds of equipment, including GNSS receivers and IMUs.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] One example application is surveying streets, where power lines, exact bridge heights, bordering trees, etc. all need to be taken into account.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] Instead of collecting each of these measurements individually in the field with a tachymeter, a 3-D model from a point cloud can be created where all of the measurements needed can be made, depending on the quality of the data collected.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p01] This eliminates the problem of forgetting to take a measurement, so long as the model is available, reliable and has an appropriate level of accuracy.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] There are a wide variety of lidar applications, in addition to the applications listed below, as it is often mentioned in national lidar dataset programs.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Companies are working to cut the cost of lidar sensors, currently anywhere from about US$1,200 to more than $12,000.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Lower prices will make lidar more attractive for new markets.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Agricultural robots have been used for a variety of purposes ranging from seed and fertilizer dispersions, sensing techniques as well as crop scouting for the task of weed control.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Lidar can help determine where to apply costly fertilizer.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] It can create a topographical map of the fields and reveal slopes and sun exposure of the farmland.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Researchers at the Agricultural Research Service used this topographical data with the farmland yield results from previous years, to categorize land into zones of high, medium, or low yield.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] This indicates where to apply fertilizer to maximize yield.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Lidar is now used to monitor insects in the field.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] The use of lidar can detect the movement and behavior of individual flying insects, with identification down to sex and species.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] In 2017 a patent application was published on this technology in the United States, Europe, and China.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Another application is crop mapping in orchards and vineyards, to detect foliage growth and the need for pruning or other maintenance, detect variations in fruit production, or count plants.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Lidar is useful in GNSS-denied situations, such as nut and fruit orchards, where foliage causes interference for agriculture equipment that would otherwise utilize a precise GNSS fix.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Lidar sensors can detect and track the relative position of rows, plants, and other markers so that farming equipment can continue operating until a GNSS fix is reestablished.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Controlling weeds requires identifying plant species.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] This can be done by using 3-D lidar and machine learning.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Lidar produces plant contours as a "point cloud" with range and reflectance values.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] This data is transformed, and features are extracted from it.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] If the species is known, the features are added as new data.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] The species is labelled and its features are initially stored as an example to identify the species in the real environment.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] This method is efficient because it uses a low-resolution lidar and supervised learning.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] It includes an easy-to-compute feature set with common statistical features which are independent of the plant size.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] In April 2025, Dallas Fort Worth International Airport announced the deployment of a lidar-based platform for real-time monitoring of passenger and vehicle flows.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Lidar has many uses in archaeology, including planning of field campaigns, mapping features under forest canopy, and overview of broad, continuous features indistinguishable from the ground.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Lidar can produce high-resolution datasets quickly and cheaply.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Lidar-derived products can be easily integrated into a geographic information system (GIS) for analysis and interpretation.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Lidar can also help to create high-resolution digital elevation models (DEMs) of archaeological sites that can reveal micro-topography that is otherwise hidden by vegetation.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] The intensity of the returned lidar signal can be used to detect features buried under flat vegetated surfaces such as fields, especially when mapping using the infrared spectrum.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] The presence of these features affects plant growth and thus the amount of infrared light reflected back.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] For example, at Fort Beauséjour – Fort Cumberland National Historic Site, Canada, lidar discovered archaeological features related to the siege of the Fort in 1755.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Features that could not be distinguished on the ground or through aerial photography were identified by overlaying hill shades of the DEM created with artificial illumination from various angles.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Another example is work at Caracol by Arlen Chase and his wife Diane Zaino Chase.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] In 2012, lidar was used to search for the legendary city of La Ciudad Blanca or "City of the Monkey God" in the La Mosquitia region of the Honduran jungle.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] During a seven-day mapping period, evidence was found of man-made structures.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] In June 2013, the rediscovery of the city of Mahendraparvata was announced.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] In southern New England, lidar was used to reveal stone walls, building foundations, abandoned roads, and other landscape features obscured in aerial photography by the region's dense forest canopy.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] In Cambodia, lidar data were used by Damian Evans and Roland Fletcher to reveal anthropogenic changes to Angkor landscape.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] In 2012, lidar revealed that the Purépecha settlement of Angamuco in Michoacán, Mexico had about as many buildings as today's Manhattan; while in 2016, its use in mapping ancient Maya causeways in northern Guatemala, revealed 17 elevated roads linking the ancient city of El Mirador to other sites.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] In 2018, archaeologists using lidar discovered more than 60,000 man-made structures in the Maya Biosphere Reserve, a "major breakthrough" that showed the Maya civilization was much larger than previously thought.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] In 2024, archaeologists using lidar discovered the Upano Valley sites.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Autonomous vehicles may use lidar for obstacle detection and avoidance to navigate safely through environments.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] The introduction of lidar was a pivotal occurrence that was the key enabler behind Stanley, the first autonomous vehicle to successfully complete the DARPA Grand Challenge.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Point cloud output from the lidar sensor provides the necessary data for robot software to determine where potential obstacles exist in the environment and where the robot is in relation to those potential obstacles.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Singapore's *Singapore-MIT Alliance for Research and Technology (SMART)* is actively developing technologies for autonomous lidar vehicles.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] The very first generations of automotive adaptive cruise control systems used only lidar sensors.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] In transportation systems, to ensure vehicle and passenger safety and to develop electronic systems that deliver driver assistance, understanding the vehicle and its surrounding environment is essential.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Lidar systems play an important role in the safety of transportation systems.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Many electronic systems which enhance driver assistance and vehicle safety such as adaptive cruise control (ACC), emergency brake assist, and anti-lock braking system (ABS) depend on the detection of a vehicle's environment to act autonomously or semi-autonomously.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Lidar mapping and estimation achieve this.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Current lidar systems use rotating hexagonal mirrors which split the laser beam.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] The upper three beams are used for vehicle and obstacles ahead, and the lower beams are used to detect lane markings and road features.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] The major advantage of using lidar is that the spatial structure is obtained and this data can be fused with other sensors such as radar, etc. to get a better picture of the vehicle environment in terms of static and dynamic properties of the objects present in the environment.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Conversely, a significant issue with lidar is the difficulty in reconstructing point cloud data in poor weather conditions.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] In heavy rain, for example, the light pulses emitted from the lidar system are partially reflected off of rain droplets which adds noise to the data, called 'echoes'.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Obstacle detection and road environment recognition using lidar, proposed by Kun Zhou et al. not only focuses on object detection and tracking but also recognizes lane marking and road features.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] As mentioned earlier, the lidar systems use rotating hexagonal mirrors that split the laser beam into six beams.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] The upper three layers are used to detect the forward objects such as vehicles and roadside objects.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] The sensor is made of weather-resistant material.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] The data detected by lidar are clustered to several segments and tracked by Kalman filter.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Data clustering here is done based on characteristics of each segment based on object model, which distinguish different objects such as vehicles, signboards, etc.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] These characteristics include the dimensions of the object, etc.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] The reflectors on the rear edges of vehicles are used to differentiate vehicles from other objects.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Object tracking is done using a two-stage Kalman filter considering the stability of tracking and the accelerated motion of objects Lidar reflective intensity data is also used for curb detection by making use of robust regression to deal with occlusions.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Road marking is detected using a modified Otsu method by distinguishing rough and shiny surfaces.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Roadside reflectors that indicate lane border are sometimes hidden due to various reasons.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Therefore, other information is needed to recognize the road border.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] The lidar used in this method can measure the reflectivity from the object.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Hence, with this data the road border can also be recognized.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Also, the usage of a sensor with a weather-robust head helps to detect the objects even in bad weather conditions.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Canopy height model before and after a flood is a good example.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Lidar can detect highly detailed canopy height data as well as its road border.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Lidar measurements help identify the spatial structure of the obstacle.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] This helps distinguish objects based on size and estimate the impact of driving over it.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Lidar systems provide better range and a large field of view, which helps in detecting obstacles on the curves.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] This is one of its major advantages over radar systems, which have a narrower field of view.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] The fusion of lidar measurement with different sensors makes the system robust and useful in real-time applications, since lidar-dependent systems cannot estimate the dynamic information about the detected object.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] It has been shown that lidar can be manipulated, such that self-driving cars are tricked into taking evasive action.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Lidar has also found many applications for mapping natural and managed landscapes such as forests, wetlands, and grasslands.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Canopy heights, biomass measurements, and leaf area can all be studied using airborne lidar systems.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Similarly, lidar is also used by many industries, including Energy and Railroad, and the Department of Transportation as a faster way of surveying.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Topographic maps can also be generated readily from lidar, including for recreational use such as in the production of orienteering maps.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Lidar has also been applied to estimate and assess the biodiversity of plants, fungi, and animals.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Using southern bull kelp in New Zealand, coastal lidar mapping data has been compared with population genomic evidence to form hypotheses regarding the occurrence and timing of prehistoric earthquake uplift events.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Lidar systems have also been applied to improve forestry management.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Measurements are used to take inventory in forest plots as well as calculate individual tree heights, crown width and crown diameter.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Other statistical analysis use lidar data to estimate total plot information such as canopy volume, mean, minimum and maximum heights, vegetation cover, biomass, and carbon density.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Aerial lidar was used to map the bush fires in Australia in early 2020.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] The data was manipulated to view bare earth, and identify healthy and burned vegetation.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] High-resolution digital elevation maps generated by airborne and stationary lidar have led to significant advances in geomorphology (the branch of geoscience concerned with the origin and evolution of the Earth surface topography).
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] In 2005 the Tour Ronde in the Mont Blanc massif became the first high alpine mountain on which lidar was employed to monitor the increasing occurrence of severe rock-fall over large rock faces allegedly caused by climate change and degradation of permafrost at high altitude.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Lidar is also used in structural geology and geophysics as a combination between airborne lidar and GNSS for the detection and study of faults, for measuring uplift.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] The output of the two technologies can produce extremely accurate elevation models for terrain – models that can even measure ground elevation through trees.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] This combination was used most famously to find the location of the Seattle Fault in Washington, United States.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] This combination also measures uplift at Mount St.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Helens by using data from before and after the 2004 uplift.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Airborne lidar systems monitor glaciers and have the ability to detect subtle amounts of growth or decline.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] A satellite-based system, the NASA ICESat, includes a lidar sub-system for this purpose.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] The NASA Airborne Topographic Mapper is also used extensively to monitor glaciers and perform coastal change analysis.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] The combination is also used by soil scientists while creating a soil survey.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] The detailed terrain modeling allows soil scientists to see slope changes and landform breaks which indicate patterns in soil spatial relationships.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Initially, based on ruby lasers, lidar for meteorological applications was constructed shortly after the invention of the laser and represents one of the first applications of laser technology.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Lidar technology has since expanded vastly in capability and lidar systems are used to perform a range of measurements that include profiling clouds, measuring winds, studying aerosols, and quantifying various atmospheric components.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Atmospheric components can in turn provide useful information including surface pressure (by measuring the absorption of oxygen or nitrogen), greenhouse gas emissions (carbon dioxide and methane), photosynthesis (carbon dioxide), fires (carbon monoxide), and humidity (water vapor).
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Atmospheric lidars can be either ground-based, airborne or satellite-based depending on the type of measurement.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] 2. by measuring the scattered reflection off the ground (when the lidar is airborne) or other hard surface.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Backscatter from the atmosphere directly gives a measure of clouds and aerosols.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Other derived measurements from backscatter such as winds or cirrus ice crystals require careful selecting of the wavelength and/or polarization detected.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] *Doppler lidar* and *Rayleigh Doppler lidar* are used to measure temperature and wind speed along the beam by measuring the frequency of the backscattered light.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] The Doppler broadening of gases in motion allows the determination of properties via the resulting frequency shift.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Scanning lidars, such as NASA's conical-scanning HARLIE, have been used to measure atmospheric wind velocity.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] The ESA wind mission *ADM-Aeolus* will be equipped with a Doppler lidar system in order to provide global measurements of vertical wind profiles.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] A doppler lidar system was used in the 2008 Summer Olympics to measure wind fields during the yacht competition.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Doppler lidar systems are also now beginning to be successfully applied in the renewable energy sector to acquire wind speed, turbulence, wind veer, and wind shear data.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Both pulsed and continuous wave systems are being used.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Pulsed systems use signal timing to obtain vertical distance resolution, whereas continuous wave systems rely on detector focusing.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] The term *eolics* has been proposed to describe the collaborative and interdisciplinary study of wind using computational fluid mechanics simulations and Doppler lidar measurements.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] The ground reflection of an airborne lidar gives a measure of surface reflectivity (assuming the atmospheric transmittance is well known) at the lidar wavelength, however, the ground reflection is typically used for making absorption measurements of the atmosphere.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] "Differential absorption lidar" (DIAL) measurements utilize two or more closely spaced (less than 1 nm) wavelengths to factor out surface reflectivity as well as other transmission losses, since these factors are relatively insensitive to wavelength.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] When tuned to the appropriate absorption lines of a particular gas, DIAL measurements can be used to determine the concentration (mixing ratio) of that particular gas in the atmosphere.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] This is referred to as an *integrated path differential absorption* (IPDA) approach, since it is a measure of the integrated absorption along the entire lidar path.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] IPDA lidars can be either pulsed or CW and typically use two or more wavelengths.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] IPDA lidars have been used for remote sensing of carbon dioxide and methane.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] In Japan, differential absorption lidar (DIAL) and Raman lidar technologies are being developed to improve the accuracy of flood forecasting and rainfall prediction.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] A research by several companies, universities, and institutes, led by Kyushu University is conducting work on meteorological sensing and flood-risk modelling under a government program.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] In May 2025, EKO Instruments began a field study on Goto Fukue Island, Nagasaki Prefecture, using a Micropulse DIAL lidar system provided by the National Center for Atmospheric Research (NSF NCAR).
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] The study compares DIAL performance with existing Raman lidar systems.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Ltd. signed a technology license agreement in February 2025 with Montana State University, NSF NCAR, and NASA, covering key DIAL-related patents.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Few military applications are known to be in place and are classified (such as the lidar-based speed measurement of the AGM-129 ACM stealth nuclear cruise missile), but a considerable amount of research is underway in their use for imaging.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Higher resolution systems collect enough detail to identify targets, such as tanks.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Examples of military applications of lidar include the Airborne Laser Mine Detection System (ALMDS) for counter-mine warfare by Areté Associates.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] A NATO report (RTO-TR-SET-098) evaluated the potential technologies to do stand-off detection for the discrimination of biological warfare agents.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] The potential technologies evaluated were long-wave infrared (LWIR), differential scattering (DISC), and ultraviolet laser-induced fluorescence (UV-LIF).
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Short-range compact spectrometric lidar based on laser-induced fluorescence (LIF) would address the presence of bio-threats in aerosol form over critical indoor, semi-enclosed and outdoor venues such as stadiums, subways, and airports.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] This near real-time capability would enable rapid detection of a bioaerosol release and allow for timely implementation of measures to protect occupants and minimize the extent of contamination.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] The Long-Range Biological Standoff Detection System (LR-BSDS) was developed for the U.S.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Army to provide the earliest possible standoff warning of a biological attack.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] It is an airborne system carried by helicopter to detect synthetic aerosol clouds containing biological and chemical agents at long range.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] The LR-BSDS, with a detection range of 30 km or more, was fielded in June 1997.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Five lidar units produced by the German company Sick AG were used for short range detection on Stanley, the autonomous car that won the 2005 DARPA Grand Challenge.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] A robotic Boeing AH-6 performed a fully autonomous flight in June 2010, including avoiding obstacles using lidar.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] The calculation of ore volumes is accomplished by periodic (monthly) scanning in areas of ore removal, then comparing surface data to the previous scan.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Lidar sensors may also be used for obstacle detection and avoidance for robotic mining vehicles such as in the Komatsu Autonomous Haulage System (AHS) used in Rio Tinto's Mine of the Future.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] A worldwide network of observatories uses lidars to measure the distance to reflectors placed on the Moon, allowing the position of the Moon to be measured with millimeter precision and tests of general relativity to be done.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] MOLA, the Mars Orbiting Laser Altimeter, used a lidar instrument in a Mars-orbiting satellite (the NASA Mars Global Surveyor) to produce a spectacularly precise global topographic survey of the red planet.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Laser altimeters produced global elevation models of Mars, the Moon (Lunar Orbiter Laser Altimeter (LOLA)), and Mercury (Mercury Laser Altimeter (MLA), NEAR–Shoemaker Laser Rangefinder (NLR)).
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Future missions will also include laser altimeter experiments such as the Ganymede Laser Altimeter (GALA) as part of the Jupiter Icy Moons Explorer (JUICE) mission.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] In September, 2008, the NASA *Phoenix* lander used lidar to detect snow in the atmosphere of Mars.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] In atmospheric physics, lidar is used as a remote detection instrument to measure densities of certain constituents of the middle and upper atmosphere, such as potassium, sodium, or molecular nitrogen and oxygen.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] These measurements can be used to calculate temperatures.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Lidar can also be used to measure wind speed and to provide information about vertical distribution of the aerosol particles.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] At the JET nuclear fusion research facility in the UK near Abingdon, Oxfordshire, lidar Thomson scattering is used to determine electron density and temperature profiles of the plasma.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Lidar has been widely used in rock mechanics for rock mass characterization and slope change detection.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Some important geomechanical properties from the rock mass can be extracted from the 3-D point clouds obtained by means of the lidar.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Some of these properties have been used to assess the geomechanical quality of the rock mass through the RMR index.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Moreover, as the orientations of discontinuities can be extracted using the existing methodologies, it is possible to assess the geomechanical quality of a rock slope through the SMR index.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] In addition to this, the comparison of different 3-D point clouds from a slope acquired at different times allows researchers to study the changes produced on the scene during this time interval as a result of rockfalls or any other landsliding processes.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] THOR is a laser designed toward measuring Earth's atmospheric conditions.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] The laser enters a cloud cover and measures the thickness of the return halo.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] The sensor has a fiber optic aperture with a width of 7+1⁄2 inches (19 cm) that is used to measure the return light.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Lidar technology is being used in robotics for the perception of the environment as well as object classification.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] The ability of lidar technology to provide three-dimensional elevation maps of the terrain, high precision distance to the ground, and approach velocity can enable safe landing of robotic and crewed vehicles with a high degree of precision.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Lidar is also widely used in robotics for simultaneous localization and mapping and is well-integrated into robot simulators.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Refer to the Military section above for further examples.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Lidar is increasingly being utilized for rangefinding and orbital element calculation of relative velocity in proximity operations and stationkeeping of spacecraft.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Lidar has also been used for atmospheric studies from space.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Short pulses of laser light beamed from a spacecraft can reflect off tiny particles in the atmosphere and back to a telescope aligned with the spacecraft laser.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] By precisely timing the lidar echo, and by measuring how much laser light is received by the telescope, scientists can accurately determine the location, distribution and nature of the particles.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] The result is a revolutionary new tool for studying constituents in the atmosphere, from cloud droplets to industrial pollutants, which are difficult to detect by other means.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Laser altimetry is used to make digital elevation maps of planets, including the Mars Orbital Laser Altimeter (MOLA) mapping of Mars, the Lunar Orbital Laser Altimeter (LOLA) and Lunar Altimeter (LALT) mapping of the Moon, and the Mercury Laser Altimeter (MLA) mapping of Mercury.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] It is also used to help navigate the helicopter *Ingenuity* in its record-setting flights over the terrain of Mars.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Airborne lidar sensors are used by companies in the remote sensing field.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] They can be used to create a DTM (digital terrain model) or DEM (digital elevation model); this is quite a common practice for larger areas as a plane can acquire 3–4 km (2–2+1⁄2 mi) wide swaths in a single flyover.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Greater vertical accuracy of below 50 mm (2 in) can be achieved with a lower flyover, even in forests, where it is able to give the height of the canopy as well as the ground elevation.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Typically, a GNSS receiver configured over a georeferenced control point is needed to link the data in with the WGS (World Geodetic System).
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Lidar is also in use in hydrographic surveying.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Depending upon the clarity of the water lidar can measure depths from 0.9 to 40 m (3 to 131 ft) with a vertical accuracy of 15 cm (6 in) and horizontal accuracy of 2.5 m (8 ft).
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Lidar has been used in the railroad industry to generate asset health reports for asset management and by departments of transportation to assess their road conditions.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] CivilMaps.com is a leading company in the field.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Lidar has been used in adaptive cruise control (ACC) systems for automobiles.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Systems such as those by Siemens, Hella, Ouster and Cepton use a lidar device mounted on the front of the vehicle, such as the bumper, to monitor the distance between the vehicle and any vehicle in front of it.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] In the event where the vehicle in front slows down or is too close, the ACC applies the brakes to slow the vehicle.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] When the road ahead is clear, the ACC allows the vehicle to accelerate to a speed preset by the driver.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] A lidar-based device, the Ceilometer, is used at airports worldwide to measure the height of clouds on runway approach paths.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Lidar can be used to increase the energy output from wind farms by accurately measuring wind speeds and wind turbulence.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Experimental lidar systems can be mounted on the nacelle of a wind turbine or integrated into the rotating spinner to measure oncoming horizontal winds, winds in the wake of the wind turbine, and proactively adjust blades to protect components and increase power.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Lidar is also used to characterise the incident wind resource for comparison with wind turbine power production to verify the performance of the wind turbine by measuring the wind turbine's power curve.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Wind farm optimization can be considered a topic in *applied eolics*.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Another aspect of lidar in wind related industry is to use computational fluid dynamics over lidar-scanned surfaces in order to assess the wind potential, which can be used for optimal wind farm placement.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Lidar can also be used to assist planners and developers in optimizing solar photovoltaic systems at the city level by determining appropriate roof tops and for determining shading losses.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Recent airborne laser scanning efforts have focused on ways to estimate the amount of solar light hitting vertical building facades, or by incorporating more detailed shading losses by considering the influence from vegetation and larger surrounding terrain.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] The 2017 exploration game *Scanner Sombre*, by Introversion Software, uses lidar as a fundamental game mechanic.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] In *Build the Earth*, lidar is used to create accurate renders of terrain in *Minecraft* to account for any errors (mainly regarding elevation) in the default generation.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] The process of rendering terrain into Build the Earth is limited by the amount of data available in region as well as the speed it takes to convert the file into block data.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Lidar technology enhances physical security by providing precise, privacy-compliant threat detection for applications such as perimeter protection, building facades, and critical infrastructure monitoring.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] These systems utilize laser-based sensors to create high-density point clouds that function reliably in challenging environmental conditions, including rain, snow, and complete darkness.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] A key advantage of modern systems is the use of 3D lidar, which creates precise volumetric detection zones capturing height, width, and depth, allowing for the accurate classification of object size and movement speed.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] The video for the 2007 song "House of Cards" by Radiohead was believed to be the first use of real-time 3-D laser scanning to record a music video.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] The range data in the video is not completely from a lidar, as structured light scanning is also used.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] In 2020, Apple introduced the fourth generation of iPad Pro with a lidar sensor integrated into the rear camera module, especially developed for augmented reality (AR) experiences.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] The feature was later included in the iPhone 12 Pro lineup and subsequent Pro models.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] On Apple devices, lidar empowers portrait mode pictures with night mode, quickens auto focus and improves accuracy in the Measure app.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] In 2022, *Wheel of Fortune* started using lidar technology to track when Vanna White moves her hand over the puzzle board to reveal letters.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] The first episode to have this technology was in the season 40 premiere.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] In flash lidar, the entire field of view is illuminated with a wide diverging laser beam in a single pulse.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] This is in contrast to conventional scanning lidar, which uses a collimated laser beam that illuminates a single point at a time, and the beam is raster scanned to illuminate the field of view point-by-point.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] This illumination method requires a different detection scheme as well.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] In both scanning and flash lidar, a time-of-flight camera is used to collect information about both the 3-D location and intensity of the light incident on it in every frame.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] However, in scanning lidar, this camera contains only a point sensor, while in flash lidar, the camera contains either a 1-D or a 2-D sensor array, each pixel of which collects 3-D location and intensity information.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] In both cases, the depth information is collected using the time of flight of the laser pulse (i.e., the time it takes each laser pulse to hit the target and return to the sensor), which requires the pulsing of the laser and acquisition by the camera to be synchronized.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] The result is a camera that takes pictures of distance, instead of colors.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Flash lidar is especially advantageous when compared to scanning lidar, when the camera, scene, or both are moving, since the entire scene is illuminated at the same time.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] With scanning lidar, motion can cause "jitter" from the lapse in time as the laser rasters over the scene.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] As with all forms of lidar, the onboard source of illumination makes flash lidar an active sensor.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] The signal that is returned is processed by embedded algorithms to produce a nearly instantaneous 3-D rendering of objects and terrain features within the field of view of the sensor.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] The laser pulse repetition frequency is sufficient for generating 3-D videos with high resolution and accuracy.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] The high frame rate of the sensor makes it a useful tool for a variety of applications that benefit from real-time visualization, such as highly precise remote landing operations.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] By immediately returning a 3-D elevation mesh of target landscapes, a flash sensor can be used to identify optimal landing zones in autonomous spacecraft landing scenarios.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Seeing at a distance requires a powerful burst of light.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] The power is limited to levels that do not damage human retinas.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] However, low-cost silicon imagers do not read light in the eye-safe spectrum.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Instead, gallium-arsenide imagers are required, which can boost costs to $200,000.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Gallium-arsenide is the same compound used to produce high-cost, high-efficiency solar panels usually used in space applications.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] Computer stereo vision has shown promise as an alternative to lidar for close-range applications.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/lidar-p02] It is significantly more cost effective when appropriate.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] An **optical time-domain reflectometer** (**OTDR**) is an optoelectronic instrument used to characterize an optical fiber.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] It is the optical equivalent of an electronic time domain reflectometer which measures the impedance of the cable or transmission line under test.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] An OTDR injects a series of optical pulses into the fiber under test and extracts, from the same end of the fiber, light that is scattered (Rayleigh backscatter) or reflected back from points along the fiber.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] The scattered or reflected light that is gathered back is used to characterize the optical fiber.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] The strength of the return pulses is measured and integrated as a function of time, and plotted as a function of length of the fiber.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] The reliability and quality of an OTDR is based on its accuracy, measurement range, ability to resolve and measure closely spaced events, measurement speed, and ability to perform satisfactorily under various environmental extremes and after various types of physical abuse.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] The instrument is also judged on the basis of its cost, features provided, size, weight, and ease of use.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] : Defined as the correctness of the measurement i.e., the difference between the measured value and the true value of the event being measured.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] : Defined as the maximum attenuation that can be placed between the instrument and the event being measured, for which the instrument will still be able to measure the event within acceptable accuracy limits.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] : Is a measure of how close two events can be spaced and still be recognized as two separate events.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] The duration of the measurement pulse and the data sampling interval create a resolution limitation for OTDRs.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] The shorter the pulse duration and the shorter the data sampling interval, the better the instrument resolution, but the shorter the measurement range.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] Resolution is also often limited when powerful reflections return to the OTDR and temporarily overload the detector.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] When this occurs, some time is required before the instrument can resolve a second fiber event.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] Some OTDR manufacturers use a “masking” procedure to improve resolution.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] The procedure shields or “masks” the detector from high-power fiber reflections, preventing detector overload and eliminating the need for detector recovery.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] Industry requirements for the reliability and quality of OTDRs are specified in the Generic Requirements for Optical Time Domain Reflectometer (OTDR) Type Equipment.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] **Hand-held OTDR and Fiber break locator**: Hand-held (formerly mini) OTDRs and fiber break locators are designed to troubleshoot fiber networks in a field environment, often using battery power.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] The two types of instruments cover the spectrum of approaches to fiber optic plant taken by communication providers.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] Hand-held, inexpensive OTDRs are intended to be easy-to-use, lightweight, sophisticated OTDRs that collect field data and perform rudimentary data analysis.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] They may be less feature rich than full-feature OTDRs.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] Often they can be used in conjunction with PC-based software to perform data collection and sophisticated data analysis.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] Hand-held OTDRs are commonly used to measure fiber links and locate fiber breaks, points of high loss, high reflectance, end-to-end loss, and Optical Return Loss (ORL).
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] Fiber break locators are intended to be low-cost instruments specifically designed to determine the location of a catastrophic fiber event, e.g., fiber break, point of high reflectance, or high loss.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] The fiber break locator is an opto-electronic tape measure designed to measure only distance to catastrophic fiber events.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] In general, hand-held OTDRs and fiber break locators are lighter and smaller, simpler to operate, and more likely to employ battery power than full-feature OTDRs.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] The intent with hand-held OTDRs and fiber break locators is to be inexpensive enough for field technicians to be equipped with one as part of a standard tool kit.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] **RTU in RFTSs**: The RTU is the testing module of the RFTS described in Generic Requirements for Remote Fiber Testing Systems (RFTSS).
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] An RFTS enables fiber to be automatically tested from a central location.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] A central computer is used to control the operation of OTDR-like test components located at key points in the fiber network.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] The test components scan the fiber to locate problems.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] If a problem is found, its location is noted and the appropriate personnel are notified to begin the repair process.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] The RFTS can also provide direct access to a database that contains historical information of the OTDR fiber traces and any other fiber records for the physical fiber plant.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] Since OTDRs and OTDR-like equipment have many uses in the communications industry, operating environments vary widely, both indoors and outdoors.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] Most often, however, these test sets are operated in controlled environments, accessing the fibers at their termination points on fiber distribution frames.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] Indoor environments include controlled areas such as central offices (COs), equipment huts, or Controlled Environment Vaults (CEVs).
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] Use in outside environments is rarer, but may include use in a manhole, aerial platform, open trench, or splicing vehicle.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] In the late 1990s, OTDR industry representatives and the OTDR user community developed a unique data format to store and analyze OTDR fiber data.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] This data was based on the specifications in GR-196, Generic Requirements for Optical Time Domain Reflectometer (OTDR) Type Equipment.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] The goal was for the data format to be truly universal, in that it was intended to be implemented by all OTDR manufacturers.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] OTDR suppliers developed the software to implement the data format.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] As they proceeded, they identified inconsistencies in the format, along with areas of misunderstanding among users.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] From 1997 to 2000, a group of OTDR supplier software specialists attempted to resolve problems and inconsistencies in what was then called the “Bellcore” OTDR Data Format.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] This group, called the OTDR Data Format Users Group (ODFUG), made progress.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] Since then, many OTDR developers continued to work with other developers to solve individual interaction problems and enable cross use between manufacturers.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] In 2011, Telcordia decided to compile industry comments on this data format into one document entitled Optical Time Domain Reflectometer (OTDR) Data Format.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] This Special Report (SR) summarizes the state of the Bellcore OTDR Data Format, renaming it as the Telcordia OTDR Data Format.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] The data format is intended for all OTDR-related equipment designed to save trace data and analysis information.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] Initial implementations require standalone software to be provided by the OTDR supplier to convert existing OTDR trace files to the SR-4731 data format and to convert files from this universal format to a format that is usable by their older OTDRs.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] This file conversion software can be developed by the hardware supplier, the end user, or a third party.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] This software also provides backward compatibility of the OTDR data format with existing equipment.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] The SR-4731 format describes binary data.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] While text information is contained in several fields, most numbers are represented as either 16-bit (2-byte) or 32-bit (4-byte) signed or unsigned integers stored as binary images.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] Byte ordering in this file format is explicitly low-byte ordering, as is common on Intel processor-based machines.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] String fields are terminated with a zero byte “\0”.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] OTDR waveform data are represented as short, unsigned integer data uniformly spaced in time, in units of decibels (dB) times 1000, referenced to the maximum power level.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] The maximum power level is set to zero, and all waveform data points are assumed to be zero or negative (the sign bit is implied), so that the minimum power level in this format is -65.535 dB, and the minimum resolution between power level steps is 0.001 dB.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] In some cases, this will not provide sufficient power range to represent all waveform points.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/optical-time-domain-reflectometer] For this reason, the use of a scale factor has been introduced to expand the data point power range.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/point-cloud] A **point cloud** is a discrete set of data points in space.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/point-cloud] The points may represent a 3D shape or object.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/point-cloud] Each point position has its set of Cartesian coordinates (X, Y, Z).
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/point-cloud] Points may contain data other than position such as RGB colors, normals, timestamps and others.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/point-cloud] Point clouds are generally produced by 3D scanners or by photogrammetry software, which measure many points on the external surfaces of objects around them.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/point-cloud] When scanning a scene in real world using Lidar, the captured point clouds contain snippets of the scene, which requires alignment to generate a full map of the scanned environment.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/point-cloud] Point clouds are often aligned with 3D models or with other point clouds, a process termed point set registration.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/point-cloud] The Iterative closest point (ICP) algorithm can be used to align two point clouds that have an overlap between them, and are separated by a rigid transform.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/point-cloud] Point clouds with elastic transforms can also be aligned by using a non-rigid variant of the ICP (NICP).
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/point-cloud] With advancements in machine learning in recent years, point cloud registration may also be done using end-to-end neural networks.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/point-cloud] For industrial metrology or inspection using industrial computed tomography, the point cloud of a manufactured part can be aligned to an existing model and compared to check for differences.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/point-cloud] Geometric dimensions and tolerances can also be extracted directly from the point cloud.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/point-cloud] While point clouds can be directly rendered and inspected, point clouds are often converted to polygon mesh or triangle mesh models, non-uniform rational B-spline (NURBS) surface models, or CAD models through a process commonly referred to as surface reconstruction.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/point-cloud] There are many techniques for converting a point cloud to a 3D surface.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/point-cloud] In geographic information systems, point clouds are one of the sources used to make digital elevation model of the terrain.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/point-cloud] They are also used to generate 3D models of urban environments.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/point-cloud] Drones are often used to collect a series of RGB images which can be later processed on a computer vision algorithm platform such as on AgiSoft Photoscan, Pix4D, DroneDeploy or Hammer Missions to create RGB point clouds from where distances and volumetric estimations can be made.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/point-cloud] Point clouds can also be used to represent volumetric data, as is sometimes done in medical imaging.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/point-cloud] Using point clouds, multi-sampling and data compression can be achieved.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/point-cloud] MPEG began standardizing point cloud compression (PCC) with a Call for Proposal (CfP) in 2017.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/point-cloud] Three categories of point clouds were identified: category 1 for static point clouds, category 2 for dynamic point clouds, and category 3 for Lidar sequences (dynamically acquired point clouds).
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/point-cloud] Two technologies were finally defined: G-PCC (Geometry-based PCC, ISO/IEC 23090 part 9) for category 1 and category 3; and V-PCC (Video-based PCC, ISO/IEC 23090 part 5) for category 2.
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/point-cloud] The first test models were developed in October 2017, one for G-PCC (TMC13) and another one for V-PCC (TMC2).
[src:lidar-sensors-deep/point-cloud] Since then, the two test models have evolved through technical contributions and collaboration, and the first version of the PCC standard specifications was expected to be finalized in 2020 as part of the ISO/IEC 23090 series on the coded representation of immersive media content.
